    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the S-1 filing, the company (which appears to be a merged entity encompassing SpaceX, Starlink, and the recently acquired xAI) frames AI not merely as a software challenge, but as a massive, physics-constrained infrastructure and engineering problem. \n\nHere is a detailed breakdown of what the filing says regarding AI infrastructure, data centers, GPU clusters, and capital expenditure plans:\n\n### 1. AI Infrastructure Buildout (Macro Context & Strategy)\n*   **Unprecedented Macro Demand:** The filing establishes that meeting global AI needs will require **$7 trillion in data center investment through 2030**. By the end of the decade, generative AI workloads are expected to consume roughly 70% of total global data-center power.\n*   **Infrastructure-Constrained Frontier AI:** Frontier AI is described as "fundamentally infrastructure-constrained." Because model performance is tied to scaling laws (compute, data, parameters), the rise of agentic AI and AGI will cause a "step-function increase" in compute requirements. \n*   **Physical Bottlenecks:** The company asserts that the primary constraints on AI growth are strictly physical: chip manufacturing, power generation, cooling, and data center infrastructure. \n*   **Orbital AI Compute:** In a unique strategic twist, the company ties its Starship launch vehicle program to AI. By reducing the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more, Starship is expected to lay the groundwork for future **"orbital AI compute"** infrastructure.\n\n### 2. Data Center Construction (Speed, Scale, and Cost Advantages)\n*   **Gigawatt-Scale Facilities (COLOSSUS):** The company owns and operates **COLOSSUS and COLOSSUS II**, which collectively provide approximately **1.0 gigawatt** of compute power, making them the largest AI training data center clusters on Earth.\n*   **First-Principles Deployment Speed:** The company highlights extreme construction velocity. COLOSSUS I was brought online in **122 days** (by repurposing an existing factory), and COLOSSUS II in just **91 days**. This is contrasted with the industry benchmark of roughly two years to bring a 100MW greenfield data center online.\n*   **Cost Efficiency & Innovations:** Construction costs for COLOSSUS II are "considerably lower than industry benchmarks" on a per-megawatt basis. This is achieved through behind-the-meter power generation, massive sustainable battery storage networks, advanced liquid cooling, and high-density rack layouts.\n*   **The Economics of Compute:** The filing notes that for companies lacking a build-cost advantage, ~30% of capital costs come from data center construction (shell, MEP, grid interconnection) and ~70% from processors/IT equipment. By lowering construction costs and time-to-grid, the company directly lowers its "cost per token."\n*   **Accounting Treatments:** Because these are significant long-term projects, the company capitalizes interest during construction ($169 million capitalized in 2025; $7 million in Q1 2026). "Construction in progress" on the balance sheet heavily features unplaced AI infrastructure.\n\n### 3. GPU Clusters & Hardware Strategy\n*   **Massive Scale:** The company\'s clusters consist of **hundreds of thousands of GPUs** operating coherently at a gigawatt scale.\n*   **Non-Linear Performance Advantages:** The filing stresses that only operators with massive, tightly integrated GPU clusters can train cutting-edge models. These large-scale systems exhibit "non-linear performance advantages that compound over time," driving higher cluster-level throughput and faster model iteration.\n*   **Vertical Integration & "Terafab":** To eliminate external supply chain bottlenecks, the company maintains full vertical integration. Beyond procuring third-party GPUs, the filing explicitly mentions the **Terafab initiative**, which aims to manufacture the company\'s own GPUs and extend its control down to the foundational processor layer.\n\n### 4. Capital Expenditure Plans for the AI Segment\n*   **Surging CapEx Numbers:** AI segment capital expenditures have grown explosively to support terrestrial data center expansion and hardware procurement:\n    *   **2023:** $463 million\n    *   **2024:** $5.63 billion\n    *   **2025:** $12.72 billion\n    *   **Q1 2026 (3 months):** $7.72 billion (up from $2.56B in Q1 2025)\n*   **Financial Impact & Profitability Horizon:** The AI segment (anchored by the **February 2026 acquisition of xAI**) is highly capital-intensive and currently operates at a significant loss (e.g., a $6.35 billion operating loss in 2025; a $2.46 billion loss in Q1 2026). \n*   **Long-Term Strategy over Near-Term Margins:** The company explicitly warns investors to expect a **"multi-year investment horizon"** before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA. Management states it may accelerate investments at any time, intentionally prioritizing long-term growth and the capture of a **$26.5 trillion potential market opportunity** over near-term profitability.\n*   **Funding the Buildout:** To sustain this massive cash burn, the company plans to utilize the full range of debt and equity financing solutions available to it as a public company.',
