ntly increased depreciation expenses. For example, Q1 2026 cost of revenue saw a **$276 million increase** in depreciation from capitalized launch and satellite costs due to the higher volume of satellites placed into orbit.\n\n### **3. Ground Infrastructure Investment**\nInvestments in ground infrastructure are deeply integrated into the Connectivity segment\'s CapEx, R&D, and operating expenses:\n*   **Capital Expenditures:** "Ground equipment costs" are cited alongside satellite costs as the primary driver of the Connectivity segment\'s rising CapEx. The company notes it has incurred, and will continue to incur, significant CapEx for the construction and expansion of "ground stations" and supporting infrastructure.\n*   **Research & Development:** The segment\'s R&D expenses heavily fund the "development, build, and testing of our next-generation satellites, Starlink Kits, and ground infrastructure."\n*   **Operating Costs:** Ground infrastructure contributes to the cost of revenue through depreciation and direct operating expenses. In Q1 2026, ground operating costs specifically drove a **$50 million increase** in operating expenses.\n*   **Future Efficiency:** Management expects Connectivity cost of revenue to increase in absolute dollars as the network grows, but anticipates it will *decrease as a percentage of revenue* over time as the company drives efficiencies in its "next-generation satellites, Starlink Kits, and ground infrastructure."',
